            </g:qualityFeatureGroup>
            <p:rationale>Each distinct communication style has specific characteristics that conflict with those of dissimilar communication styles. However, integration between applications often goes through a number of intermediate components (such as connectors, adapters and flows in the service bus), between which a diverse number of communication styles might be chosen. If these disparate communication styles do not connect well with each other, then the end-to-end system integration no longer contains the desired characteristics. Let"s look at a specific example; a request / response style that is designed to quickly deliver an answer to the end-user. When this style is combined with an asynchronous style (deferred synchronous), the receiver will have to wait longer than desired, system time-outs may occur in greater speed and frequency, and system resources are retained longer than is necessary. Conversely, the reliability typically desired in an asynchronous communication is canceled out if an unreliable transport is used at any step in the process.</p:rationale>
            <p:implications>If real-time information is requested, then all communications in the chain should use a synchronous transport mechanism. If reliable communication is required, then all communications in the chain should use a reliable transport mechanism. </p:implications>
